Indiscriminate monitoring refers to mass surveillance techniques that collect data on everyone — not just specific suspects. Instead of targeting known threats, systems gather messages, calls, metadata, locations, and internet habits from entire populations. This data is often stored and analyzed automatically.

Even if someone "has nothing to hide," they can be profiled, misinterpreted, or targeted later due to changing laws or political motives. Unlike selective surveillance, it's not based on warrants. Tools like air-gapped end-to-end encryption break this chain by limiting what can be accessed in the first place — even if systems tap the rest.